\begin_layout Section
A Theoretical Framework and Elasticities
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Static Labor Supply Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A worker's utility maximization problem is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{C_{t},L_{t}}{\max\ }U(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 are within-period consumption, leisure hours and individual attributes,
 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subject to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full income
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 budget constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}+W_{t}L_{t}=Y_{t}+W_{t}T
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}$
\end_inset

 is hourly wage rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is non-labor income, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the total time available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Marshallian Elasticity of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
FOCs for an interior solution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U_{C}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t}) & = & \lambda_{t}\\
U_{L}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t}) & = & \lambda_{t}W_{t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An equivalent representation of the FOCs is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U_{C}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})}{U_{L}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})}=\frac{1}{W_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solving the FOCs yields the Marshallian demand functions for consumption
 and leisure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{t}^{M*} & = & C^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})\\
L_{t}^{M*} & = & L^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Marshallian Elasticity of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Marshallian labor supply function is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{t}^{M*} & = & T-L^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})\\
 & \equiv & H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Marshallian (uncompensated) elasticity of labor supply is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{M}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln(W_{t})}\biggl|_{Y_{t}=\bar{Y}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Hicksian Elasticity of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A dual problem for a worker is the expenditure minimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{C_{t},L_{t}}{\min}\ C_{t}+W_{t}L_{t}
\]

\end_inset

subject to a given utility level:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})=U_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solving the minimization problem gives the Hicksian demand functions for
 consumption and leisure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{t}^{H*} & = & C^{M}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})\\
L_{t}^{H*} & = & L^{M}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Hicksian Elasticity of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Hicksian labor supply function is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{t}^{H*} & = & T-L^{M}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})\\
 & \equiv & H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Hicksian (compensated) elasticity of labor supply is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{H}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}\Biggl|_{U_{t}=\bar{U}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Elasticities of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two concepts of the elasticity of labor supply in the static model: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The Marshallian elasticity of labor supply: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{M}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln(W_{t})}\biggl|_{Y_{t}=\bar{Y}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

is the percentage change in worker's hours of work when the wage rate increases
 by 1%, holding the amount of 
\series bold
non-labor income
\series default
 constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Hicksian elasticity of labor supply:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{H}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}\Biggl|_{U_{t}=\bar{U}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

is the percentage change in worker's hours of work when the wage rate increases
 by 1%, holding the 
\series bold
utility level
\series default
 constant.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Relative Size of Elasticities of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What about the relative size of the two elasticities?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})=H^{M}(W_{t},e(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t}),X_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can derive the Slutsky equation:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})}{\partial W_{t}}=\frac{\partial H^{M}(W_{t},e(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t}),X_{t})}{\partial W_{t}}-\frac{\partial H^{M}(W_{t},e(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t}),X_{t})}{\partial Y_{t}}H_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Slutsky equation in elasticity form is:
\size small

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{Hicksian}{\underbrace{\frac{\partial\ln H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}}}=\underset{Marshallian}{\underbrace{\frac{\partial\ln H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}}}-\underset{Income\ effect}{\underbrace{\frac{\partial\ln H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln Y_{t}}\frac{H_{t}W_{t}}{Y_{t}}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So if leisure is a normal good, we have:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{H}>E_{t}^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Dynamic Model of Labor Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A full lifecycle model is characterized by a utility function of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(C_{1},L_{1},X_{1},...,C_{T},L_{T},X_{T})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This full model is empirically intractable, so all studies assume some form
 of separability in time:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{U}(U(C_{1},L_{1},X_{1}),...,U(C_{T},L_{T},X_{T}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subject to the intertemporal budget constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{t+1}=(1+r_{t})A_{t}+W_{t}H_{t}+Y_{t}-C_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the real value of assets and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the real rate of return earned on assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Two-Stage Budgeting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The dynamic problem can be broken down into two sub-problems:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
(Stage 2) In each subperiod, the agent maximizes the period utility as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\underset{C_{t},L_{t}}{\max}U(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})\\
s.t.\ C_{t}+W_{t}L_{t}=W_{t}T+Y_{t}+(1+r_{t})A_{t}-A_{t+1}\\
\equiv W_{t}T+Y_{t}^{C}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Notice that this looks exactly the same as in the static case, only except
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{C}$
\end_inset

.
 So the within-period marginal rate of substitution conditions continue
 to characterize behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(Stage 1) Choose the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{C}$
\end_inset

 for each period.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Marshallian and Hicksian Elasticities in the Dynamic Setting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Marshallian elasticity can be derived in the same way as in the static
 framework.
 The only difference here is to condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{C}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And the Hicksian elasticity can be recovered through the Slutsky equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Recursive Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Representing the problem by using the Bellman Equation:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
V(A_{t})=\underset{C_{t},L_{t}}{\max}[U(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t})+\kappa V(A_{t+1})]\\
s.t.\ A_{t+1}=(1+r_{t})A_{t}+W_{t}H_{t}+Y_{t}-C_{t}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\size default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is a discount factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
FOCs:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U_{C}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t}) & = & \lambda_{t}\label{eq:U_c_Euler}\\
U_{L}(C_{t},L_{t},X_{t}) & = & \lambda_{t}W_{t}\label{eq:U_L_Euler}\\
\kappa V'(A_{t+1}) & = & \lambda_{t}\label{eq:E_A_Euler}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Envelop Theorem implies:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V'(A_{t})=\lambda_{t}(1+r_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Frisch Elasticities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Combining Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E_A_Euler"

\end_inset

) and the Envelop Theorem condition gives the Euler condition:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{t}=\kappa(1+r_{t+1})\lambda_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Beside the Euler equation, the other FOCs are the same as in the static
 case.
 The Euler equation determines how to allocate wealth across periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solving the FOCs (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U_c_Euler"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U_L_Euler"

\end_inset

) (two equations and two unknowns) gives Frisch demand functions for consumption
 and leisure:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{t}^{F*} & = & C^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})\\
L_{t}^{F*} & = & C^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\size default
in which the marginal utility of wealth parameter serves as the sufficient
 statistic which captures all the information from other periods that is
 needed to solve the current period maximization problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Frisch Elasticities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And the Frisch labor supply function is:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{t}^{F*} & = & T-C^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})\\
 & = & H^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Frisch elasticity of labor supply is defined as:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{F}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}\Biggl|_{\lambda_{t}=\bar{\lambda}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\size default
which is the percentage change in worker's hours of work when the wage rate
 increases by 1%, holding the 
\series bold
marginal utility of wealth
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

, constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Euler Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall the Euler Equation is:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa(1+r_{t+1})\lambda_{t+1}=\lambda_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This implies a time path for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ln\lambda_{t} & = & \ln\lambda_{t-1}-\ln\kappa(1+r_{t})\\
 & \equiv & \ln\lambda_{t-1}+b_{t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Repeating substitution yields:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\lambda_{t}=\sum_{j=1}^{t}b_{j}+\ln\lambda_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, holding 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 constant is the same as holding the initial level of the marginal utility
 of wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

, constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Three Definitions of Elasticities in the Dynamic Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Marshallian elasticity of labor supply holds the 
\series bold
consumption-based income variable
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{C}$
\end_inset

, constant:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{M}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{M}(W_{t},Y_{t}^{C},X_{t})}{\partial\ln(W_{t})}\biggl|_{Y_{t}^{C}=\bar{Y}_{t}^{C}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Hicksian elasticity of labor supply holds the 
\series bold
period utility level,
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{t},$
\end_inset

 constant:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{H}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{H}(W_{t},U_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}\Biggl|_{U_{t}=\bar{U}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Frisch elasticity of labor supply holds the 
\series bold
marginal utility of wealth
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t},$
\end_inset

 constant:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{F}=\frac{\partial\ln H^{F}(W_{t},\lambda_{t},X_{t})}{\partial\ln W_{t}}\Biggl|_{\lambda_{t}=\bar{\lambda}_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
MaCurdy (1981) and Browning et al.
 (1985) show that the Frisch elasticity is the largest of the three:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{t}^{F}>E_{t}^{H}>E_{t}^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Empirical Specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Basic Empirical Specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A prototype empirical specification:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln H_{t}=\alpha\ln W_{t}+\beta Q_{t}+e_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of controls, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a stochastic unobservable term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The interpretation of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 depends on the chosen vector 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Static Specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Control variables in the conventional static specification:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta Q_{t}=\rho X_{t}+\theta Y_{t}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

taste shifter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a measure of non-labor income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the static model is correct, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the Marshallian wage elasticity.
 But we need to assume that either the consumers behave completely myopically,
 or the capital markets are completely constrained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Two-Stage Budgeting Specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Marshallian wage elasticity in the dynamic model can be estimated by
 controlling for:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta Q_{t}=\rho X_{t}+\theta Y_{t}^{C}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}^{C}$
\end_inset

 is the consumption-based income measure.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 estimates the wage effect holding the first-stage income allocation constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This captures the impact of anticipated wage movements through time, but
 does not capture the impact of shifts of the wage profile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Frisch Specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It can be shown that if the labor supply and consumption are explicitly
 additive in the utility function, the Frisch elasticity of labor supply
 can be estimated by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\ln H_{t}=b+\rho\Delta X_{t}+\alpha\Delta\ln W_{t}+\Delta e_{t}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
