\begin_layout BeginFrame
Extending the Unitary Labor Supply Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The standard unitary labor supply model has many limitations:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The income pooling assumption is rejected in many empirical literature (e.g.
 Thomas, 1990)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cannot study intrahousehold allocation and within-household inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Policy makers are also interested in individual well-being
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Need to study how changes in outside options would affect behaviors and
 welfare
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A collective framework modeling household joint decisions on labor market
 participation tends to address these limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Collective Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the framework in Blundell et al (2007)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The collective model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\underset{h^{f},h^{m},C^{f},C^{m}}{\max}\ U^{f}[1-h^{f},C^{f}]\\
U^{m}[1-h^{m},C^{m}]\geq\bar{u}^{m}(w_{f,}w_{m},y)\\
C=w_{f}h^{f}+w_{m}h^{m}+y\\
0\leq h^{f}\leq1\\
h^{m}\in\{0,1\}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}^{m}(w_{f},w_{m},y)$
\end_inset

 is the level of utility member 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can achieve given 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{f},\ w_{m},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Solving the Collective Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
If Male Participates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conditional on male's participation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U^{m}(C^{m},0)=\bar{u}^{m}(w_{f},w_{m},y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Invert the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{m}(\cdot,0)$
\end_inset

 gives the 
\series bold
sharing rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{m}=V^{m}[\bar{u}^{m}(w_{f},w_{m},y)]\equiv\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Solving the Collective Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
If Male Participates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus member 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 's optimization problem is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\underset{h^{f},C^{f}}{\max}\ U^{f}[1-h^{f},C^{f}]\\
C^{f}=w_{f}h^{f}+y+w_{m}-\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y)\\
0\leq h^{f}\leq1
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This gives female labor supply function conditional on male's participation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{W}^{f}(w_{f},w_{m},y)=H^{f}[w_{f},y+w_{m}-\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y)]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus an implication of the collective model is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1-\Psi_{w_{m}}}{1-\Psi_{y}}=\frac{h_{w_{m}}^{f}}{h_{y}^{f}}=A(w_{f},w_{m},y)\label{eq:rest1_coll}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Solving the Collective Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
If Male Doesn't Participate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conditional on male's non-participation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U^{m}(C^{m},1)=\bar{u}^{m}(w_{f},w_{m},y)=V_{m}^{-1}(\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Invert the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{m}(\cdot,1)$
\end_inset

 gives the 
\series bold
sharing rule
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{m}=W^{m}[V_{m}^{-1}(\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y))]\equiv F(\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

's utility maximization gives the female labor supply function conditional
 on male's non-participation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{N}^{f}(w_{f},w_{m},y)=H^{f}[w_{f},y-F(\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y))]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So the second implication of the collective model is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{-F'\Psi_{w_{m}}}{1-F'\Psi_{y}}=\frac{h_{w_{m}}^{f}}{h_{y}^{f}}=B(w_{f},w_{m},y)\label{eq:cons2_coll}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Participation Decision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The participation frontier, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, is characterized by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall(w_{f},w_{m},y)\in L,\ \Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y)-F(\Psi(w_{f},w_{m},y))=w_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(w_{f},y)$
\end_inset

 be the reservation wage.
 So:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(w_{f},\gamma(w_{f},y),y)-F(\Psi(w_{f},\gamma(w_{f},y),y))=\gamma(w_{f},y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This gives two more implications of the collective model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
(\Psi_{y}+\gamma_{y}\Psi_{w_{m}}) & = & \frac{\gamma_{y}}{(1-F')}\label{eq:rest3_coll}\\
\Psi_{w_{f}} & = & \frac{\gamma_{w_{f}}}{\gamma_{y}}\Psi_{y}\label{eq:rest4_coll}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Restrictions From the Collective Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Four restrictions from the collective model (Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rest1_coll"

\end_inset

) - (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rest4_coll"

\end_inset

)):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{1-\Psi_{w_{m}}}{1-\Psi_{y}} & = & \frac{h_{w_{m}}^{f}}{h_{y}^{f}}=A(w_{f},w_{m},y)\\
\frac{-F'\Psi_{w_{m}}}{1-F'\Psi_{y}} & = & \frac{h_{w_{m}}^{f}}{h_{y}^{f}}=B(w_{f},w_{m},y)\\
(\Psi_{y}+\gamma_{y}\Psi_{w_{m}}) & = & \frac{\gamma_{y}}{(1-F')}\\
\Psi_{w_{f}} & = & \frac{\gamma_{w_{f}}}{\gamma_{y}}\Psi_{y}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The preferences and the sharing rules can be recovered up to an additive
 constant everywhere where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{f}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In Lise and Seitz (2011), the location of the sharing rule is identified
 by assuming that when husbands and wives have equal wages, they share resources
 equally.
\end_layout

